BookSources/978-0-19-722416-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-722416-8">978-0-19-722416-8</a>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Werner Rolevinck, <i><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/servlet/SirveObras/80248064097793506388868/index.htm">Fasciculus temporum</a></i>.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">While it is increasingly common to place <i>AD</i> after a date by analogy to the use of <i>BC</i>, formal English usage adheres to the traditional practice of placing the abbreviation before the year as in Latin (e.g., <span class="nowrap">100 BC</span>, but <span class="nowrap">AD 100</span>).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">V. Grumel, <i>La chronologie</i> (1958), page 30.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Jean Meeus, <i>Astronomical algorithms</i> (Richmond, Virginia: Willmann-Bell, 1991) 60.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ub.uni-kiel.de/digiport/bis1800/Arch3_436.html">Tabulae Rudolphinae \xe2\x80\x93 Ioannes Keplerus</a> (1627) 191 (42), 197 (48), 203 (54), 209 (60), 215 (66), 221 (72), 227 (78).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=BjygAAAAMAAJ&amp;printsec=frontcover#PPP35,M1">Tabulae Astronomicae \xe2\x80\x93 Philippo de la Hire</a> (1702), Tabul\xc3\xa6 15, 21, 39, 47, 55, 6